  "prompt": "How is WhatsApp able to show the blurred image even after deleting the original copy from the gallery?",
  "response": "WhatsApp can show a blurred preview of an image even after you delete the original copy from your gallery because it keeps a cached version of the image on its servers or local storage. Here\u2019s a detailed explanation of how this works:\n\n1. **Caching**: When you send or receive an image on WhatsApp, a compressed version of the image is created and stored temporarily in the app\u2019s cache. Even if you delete the original image from your device\u2019s gallery, the cached version remains within WhatsApp.\n\n2. **Thumbnails**: WhatsApp generates and stores thumbnail previews of images for use in chats. These thumbnails are smaller and lower resolution versions of the original images. The blurred preview you see is likely generated from this thumbnail, which remains in the app\u2019s local storage or servers.\n\n3. **Messages Database**: WhatsApp keeps a local database on your device that logs media files associated with chats. When you delete an image from your gallery, it doesn't necessarily get removed from this database or its associated cache, which is why WhatsApp can still display a preview of the deleted image.\n\n4. **Cloud Backup**: If you have enabled cloud backups for WhatsApp (such as Google Drive on Android or iCloud on iOS), the image might still exist in your backup, allowing WhatsApp to access and show preview even if the local copy has been deleted.\n\nThis mechanism ensures users can still view previews of images in their chat history despite deletion from the gallery, enhancing the user experience by maintaining continuity in conversations.",
